Bonus problem (10 points)

Use a pencil to compute \(BIC - AIC\). The answer will depend on \(p\) and \(n\) so lets call it \(f(p,n)\).
Using latex instead of a pencil would make this part look really good.

Write an R function called AICfromBIC() to compute \(AIC\) from \(BIC\). Inputs to your function should be \(n, p\) and \(BIC\). Inside the function theres not much to do: compute \(f(p,n)\) and then return \(BIC - f(p,n)\)

Use your function to convert \(BIC\) values to \(AIC\) in parts a, b, and c.Then use \(AIC\) to identify the optimal model in each part.


AICfromBIC <- function(n, p, BIC) {
  for(p in 1:p) {
  AIC <- BIC - log(n) * p + 2 * p
}
return(AIC)
}
